\p
\v 28 If a bull gores a man or a woman¦35714 and \add #they\add* die, the bull must certainly¦35716 be \add ≈killed by throwing rocks at it\add*. The owner¦35724 of the animal is \add to be considered\add* innocent, \add but\add* its meat mustn't be eaten¦35720.
\v 29 But if the bull had a habit of goring in the past and its owner was warned¦35734 but didn't keep it \add fenced\add* in, and it kills¦35738 a man or a woman¦35741, then the ox must be \add ≈killed by throwing rocks at it\add* and its owner must also be put to death.
\v 30 If a ransom payment is demanded instead, \add @the owner\add* may buy back \add #their\add* life¦35756 by paying the full amount demanded.
\v 31 Those rules also apply if the bull gores a \add person's\add* son or daughter¦35769.
\v 32 If the ox gores a male or female¦35782 slave, \add @its owner\add* must give thirty¦35785 silver¦35783 shekels¦35786 to the \add slave owner\add* and the bull must be \add ≈killed by throwing rocks at it\add*.
